  "notes": [
    "Please visit the department's website to learn more about this minor: https://engineering.ucsc.edu/departments/computer-science-and-engineering/ PREPARATION FOR THE MINOR CSE 12: Computer Systems and Assembly Language and Lab CSE 13S: Computer Systems and C Programming OR ECE 13: Computer Systems and C Programming CSE 16: Applied Discrete Mathematics CSE 20: Beginning Programming in Python CSE 30: Programming Abstractions: Python MATH 19A: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics MATH 19B: Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics AM 20: Mathematical Methods for Engineers II OR MATH 24: Ordinary Differential Equations Plus one of the following lecture/lab combinations: PHYS 5A: Introduction to Physics I AND PHYS 5L: Introduction to Physics I Laboratory OR PHYS 6A: Introductory Physics I AND PHYS 6L: Introductory Physics I Laboratory Plus one of the following lecture/lab combinations: PHYS 5C: Introduction to Physics III AND PHYS 5N: Introduction to Physics III Laboratory OR PHYS 6C: Introductory Physics III AND PHYS 6N: Introductory Physics III Laboratory ECE 101: Introduction to Electronic Circuits AND ECE 101L: Introduction to Electronic Circuits Laboratory",
    "UC Santa Cruz students have the option to complete one or more minors, provided they complete all of the required coursework for the minor(s). The sponsoring department establishes the course requirements for a minor. The minor involves substantial work in the discipline and requires no fewer than 25 upper-division or graduate credits. The minor appears on the student's official transcript but not on the diploma. Students do not apply for admission into a minor when applying to UC Santa Cruz. If interested in completing a minor, transfer students must contact the department sponsoring the minor after enrolling at UCSC."
